{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17515239","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17515239"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:30:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:30:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12423"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12423"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.01,0.02,0.8,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4931"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107368"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4931"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12423"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89854"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2840"},{"type":"tags","id":"4841"},{"type":"tags","id":"6281"},{"type":"tags","id":"8851"},{"type":"tags","id":"9386"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8062"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8068"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34734"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107368","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107368"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman is being reviewed in the oncology clinic for follow-up of recently diagnosed and treated diffuse large B cell lymphoma. Two months ago she was prescribed metoclopramide for side effects of severe chemotherapy-induced nausea and vomiting. She is still taking this medication. On review she complains of new-onset muscle stiffness. She has difficulty doing buttons, performing other fine movements and describes a feeling of inflexibility and resistance when moving her both hands. She does not report any other symptoms. On examination she has a loss of facial expression and there is\u00a0bilaterally reduced arm swing. She has cogwheel rigidity in the wrists bilaterally with symmetry. No tremor is observed.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Commence oral baclofen","Refer to physiotherapy","Commence oral selegiline","Replace metoclopramide with ondansetron","Commence carbidopa/levodopa"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient shows signs and symptoms consistent with Parkinsonism. Among all the causes, \u003Cstrong\u003Edrug-induced Parkinsonism\u003C/strong\u003E (DIP) is the second-most common aetiology. Development of Parkinsonism after commencement of a potentially offending drug, particularly within one year, should raise the suspicion of DIP. Although the clinical features of DIP and Parkinson\u0027s disease (PD) are often indistinguishable, they might be some clinical clues. DIP is more associated with prominent bradykinesia and rigidity, often with bilateral onset and symmetry. Autonomic dysfunction is more seen in PD and it can sometimes precede the onset of motor symptoms. Even if the presentation might be more consistent with DIP, a definitive diagnosis of it can only be given when symptoms resolve after cessation of the suspected medication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMetoclopramide, a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecentrally and peripherally acting D2 receptor blocker\u003C/strong\u003E, can act on the basal ganglia to cause extrapyramidal symptoms. The most effective way to manage DIP is to \u003Cstrong\u003Ediscontinue the offending drug\u003C/strong\u003E. Ondansetron, a 5-HT3 antagonist, can be use safely in patients with Parkinsonism as an alternative to metoclopramide. Baclofen is not recommended in treating Parkinsonism. Though physiotherapy might offer some help, discontinuing the drug removes the root cause. Carbidopa/levodopa has been tried in the management of DIP, but its evidence of efficacy is often inconsistent and the effect is usually modest. Selegiline, a MAO inhibitor, is an adjunct therapy to levodopa. However, its effect in treating DIP is also unclear. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["DIP should be considered in any case of Parkinsonism, especially if a potentially offending drug has been commenced.","The definitive management of DIP is to discontinue the suspected offending drug, if the clinical context allows."],"references":["Wyant AJ, Chou KL. Drug-induced parkinsonism. 2022 Sep [cited 2023 Jan 28]. In: UpToDate [Internet]. Waltham (MA): UpToDate, Inc. c2018 - . Available from: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/drug-induced-parkinsonism?search=Drug-induced%20parkinsonism\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=1~56\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=1","Shin HW, Chung SJ. Drug-induced parkinsonism. J Clin Neurol. 2012 Mar;8(1):15-21. doi: 10.3988/jcn.2012.8.1.15. Epub 2012 Mar 31. PMID: 22523509; PMCID: PMC3325428. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22523509/","Undeberg MR, McKeirnan KC, Easley D. Respecting the Patient\u0027s Choice: A Case of Possible Drug-Induced Parkinsonism. Pharmacy (Basel). 2022 Jan 4;10(1):10. doi: 10.3390/pharmacy10010010. PMID: 35076621; PMCID: PMC8788564. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8788564/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89854"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12423"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89854","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89854"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-29T